<h3 class="wp-block-heading" id="Barbell-Seal-Row">Barbell Seal Row</h3>



<p>The barbell seal row is a beneficial exercise for maximizing back <a href="https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/pmc/articles/PMC6950543/" target="_blank" rel="noreferrer noopener nofollow">muscle hypertrophy</a>. This consists in increasing the muscle cell count and size. It primarily targets the latissimus dorsi, trapezius, and shoulder muscles to lift the barbell. The bench supports the chest allowing greater focus on engaging the prime movers.&nbsp;</p>



<p>Secondary movers include the biceps and brachialis muscles during elbow flexion. As a result, this movement is an effective upper-body strengthener.</p>



<p>This exercise also improves spinal stability and performance in daily tasks requiring pulling, lifting, and rowing. Program it into an upper-body lift or functional full-body routine to achieve the most benefits.</p>



<figure class="wp-block-embed is-type-video is-provider-vimeo wp-block-embed-vimeo wp-embed-aspect-16-9 wp-has-aspect-ratio vimeo-custom"><div class="wp-block-embed__wrapper">
<iframe loading="lazy" title="Barbell Seal Row" src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/1008716678?dnt=1&amp;app_id=122963" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" allow="autoplay; fullscreen; picture-in-picture; clipboard-write"></iframe>
</div><figcaption class="wp-element-caption">Barbell Seal Row Guide. Video: Aliaksandr Makatserchyk</figcaption></figure>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">How To Do</h4>



<ol>
<li>Place a barbell on a rack under a flat bench with the appropriate weight for your fitness level and goals.</li>



<li>Lie on the bench face down and torso long and flat.</li>



<li>Grasp the barbell with both hands using an overhand grip (palms facing down).</li>



<li>Inhale and engage your core.</li>



<li>Exhale as you lift the barbell towards your midline. Focus on squeezing your back and shoulder muscles to maximize activation.</li>



<li>Hold at the top for one count, maintaining control.</li>



<li>Slowly lower the barbell back down, maintaining control.</li>



<li>Repeat for the desired number of reps and sets.</li>
</ol>



<h4 class="wp-block-heading">Tips</h4>



<ul>
<li>Avoid using momentum or swinging the barbell during the movement.</li>



<li>Keep a slight bend in the elbows at the bottom of the movement. Don’t drop the barbell back to the rack at any point.</li>



<li>Focus on proper breathing techniques. Inhale to engage before starting, exhale to lift the weight, and inhale as you lower back down.</li>
</ul>



